{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609044"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:40:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:40:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16070"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16070"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.23,0.12,0,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63795"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8761"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49225"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"10863"},{"type":"tags","id":"10866"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63795"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECertain pathogenic fungi can exist in two distinct morphological forms depending on environmental conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristic growth pattern of dimorphic fungi?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mold at 25\u00b0C and yeast at 37\u00b0C","Yeast at 25\u00b0C and mold at 37\u00b0C","Yeast in aerobic conditions and mold in anaerobic conditions","Mold in tissue and yeast in culture media","Yeast in acidic conditions and mold in alkaline conditions"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDimorphic fungi exhibit temperature-dependent morphological switching. They grow as \u003Cstrong\u003Emold at 25\u00b0C and yeast at 37\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E. This characteristic is important for their pathogenicity, as the yeast form is typically seen in human infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMorphology of dimorphic fungi is not as commonly influenced by \u003Cstrong\u003EpH, oxygen availability \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Eculture media/tissue \u003C/strong\u003Edifferential conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of dimorphic fungi include \u003Cem\u003EHistoplasma capsulatum\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EBlastomyces dermatitidis\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003ECoccidioides immitis\u003C/em\u003E. This temperature-dependent dimorphism is an important virulence factor that allows these organisms to adapt to different environmental conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dimorphic fungi exist as molds at room temperature (25\u00b0C) and as yeasts at body temperature (37\u00b0C).","The most clinically significant dimorphic fungi include Histoplasma capsulatum, Blastomyces dermatitidis, and Coccidioides immitis."],"references":["Gauthier GM. Dimorphism in fungal pathogens of mammals, plants, and insects. PLoS Pathog. 2015 Feb 12;11(2):e1004608. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4335504/#ppat.1004608.t001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16070"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49225"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T16:37:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T23:11:26+10:30"},"relations